						               													<description>OMEGA was born as an experiment on complexity and intuitive arithmetic. Both concepts teamed up to create this little monster. It feels like a cross between Hex and Go.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;In OMEGA, players try to create groups of their colors by placing stones in a hexagonal grid, in order to score the most points. But each player places stones of all colors in play.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The final score for each color is calculated by multiplying the sizes of the different groups of that color.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Thanks to the 6 acrylic 'corners' included in the game, it can be played on various board sizes. From 5-hexes side to 10-hexes side. Other board shapes can be configured, too.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;You will soon realize that you don&amp;acute;t need to calculate your score during play (multiplying your group values). Use an intuitive strategy instead. How? You must figure it out by yourself.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;2-player games of size beyond 8 are only recommended for experienced players and scores are often gigantic.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;OMEGA was initially designed for 2 players. The designer then added the 3 and 4 player option, but the gameplay is completely different.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
